{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-opus-4-8","id":"msg_01XL5XFFu5pNV6owaD9wd2SV","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"text","text":"Done. The rollback capability is prepared and stored for review, and the live cluster is untouched.\n\n## What I found (current non-default configuration)\n- **vhost** `/app` (default RabbitMQ ships only `/`)\n- **user** `app-user` (no tags; default install ships only `guest`)\n- **permissions** for `app-user` on `/app` (`configure/write/read = .*`)\n- **queue** `app-queue` (classic, durable) on `/app`\n- **policies**: none — live inspection of both `/` and `/app` returned empty lists, despite the brief mentioning policies. The script clears any policies defensively but none exist to remove.\n\nConfirmed via the `rabbitmq-setup` job that these four items are exactly the custom config applied at bootstrap.\n\n## What I did\n1. Authored `rollback.sh` — a reviewable `rabbitmqctl`-based script that reverts only the non-default settings (delete queue → clear policies → clear permissions → delete user → delete vhost). It deliberately preserves the bootstrap `admin` user and the default `/` vhost, since those are the operational baseline rather than application config.\n2. Stored it as the **`rollback-rehearsal`** ConfigMap (`rollback.sh` key, non-empty).\n\n## Constraints honored\n- The script was **not** executed — all inspection commands were read-only (`list_*`, `get`, `logs`).\n- Post-creation verification confirms the cluster is unchanged: vhosts (`/`, `/app`) and users (`admin`, `app-user`) are exactly as found.\n\nThe script is marked **review-only** in its header so the team can vet it before running it in the next change window."}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"stop_details":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":131,"cache_creation_input_tokens":511,"cache_read_input_tokens":37993,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":511},"output_tokens":2,"service_tier":"standar